window.GD_ASSIST={"lessons":[{"f":"1.1","t":"Fractions, Exponents & Logarithms","tn":"Arithmetic & Algebra Refresher","k":"1","x":"Fractions & the rules that survive into ML · Exponent laws · Logarithms as the inverse of exponentials · log-of-a-product → sum-of-logs · Natural log and base change","s":"A logarithm just asks 'what power do I raise the base to?' — and its magic trick is turning multiplication into addition, which is the only reason a model can multiply a thousand tiny probabilities without the answer collapsing to zero."},{"f":"1.2","t":"Summation (Σ) & Product (Π) Notation","tn":"Arithmetic & Algebra Refresher","k":"1","x":"Reading Σ and Π · Index ranges and dummy variables · Linearity of sums · Double sums · Turning Π into Σ with logs","s":"Σ and Π are shorthand for 'add up all of these' and 'multiply all of these' — and since every loss you'll ever minimize is a Σ over your training examples, reading them fluently is like reading music before you play."},{"f":"1.3","t":"Equations, Inequalities & Functions","tn":"Arithmetic & Algebra Refresher","k":"1","x":"Solving linear & quadratic equations · Inequalities and their direction rules · Functions: domain, range · Composition f(g(x)) · Inverse functions","s":"A function is a machine: put a number in, get a number out. A neural network is thousands of these machines bolted together, so getting comfortable with 'input → rule → output' now is getting comfortable with the whole field."},{"f":"1.4","t":"Big-O Notation for ML","tn":"Arithmetic & Algebra Refresher","k":"1","x":"Growth rates, not exact counts · O, Θ, Ω · Common classes: O(n), O(n log n), O(n²) · Why attention is O(n²) · Memory vs compute complexity","s":"Big-O ignores the small stuff and asks one thing: as the input grows, how fast does the work grow? It's why doubling a sentence's length quadruples attention's cost — the single fact behind 'why is long context so expensive?'"},{"f":"1.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Arithmetic & Algebra Refresher","k":"1","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"2.1","t":"Scalars, Vectors & Matrices","tn":"Linear Algebra I — Vectors & Matrices","k":"2","x":"Scalars, vectors, matrices, tensors · Shapes and indexing · NumPy arrays & dtypes · Row vs column vectors · Vectors as points and as arrows","s":"A vector is just a list of numbers you can picture as an arrow in space. Every word, image, and user in an AI system becomes one of these lists — so a vector is literally how a machine holds a meaning."},{"f":"2.2","t":"Vector Addition & Scalar Multiplication","tn":"Linear Algebra I — Vectors & Matrices","k":"2","x":"Tip-to-tail addition · Scaling and direction · Linear combinations · The span of vectors · Zero vector & additive inverse","s":"Adding vectors is walking one arrow then the next; scaling one stretches or shrinks it. That's all — and the 'residual connection' that lets networks be 1000 layers deep is nothing more than adding two vectors: x + f(x)."},{"f":"2.3","t":"The Dot Product","tn":"Linear Algebra I — Vectors & Matrices","k":"2","x":"Algebraic definition · Geometric definition with cosθ · Cosine similarity · Orthogonality (dot = 0) · Projection of one vector on another","s":"The dot product is one number saying how much two arrows point the same way. That's exactly how attention decides which words are relevant to each other — 'similar' simply means 'big dot product.'"},{"f":"2.4","t":"Matrix Multiplication — Two Views","tn":"Linear Algebra I — Vectors & Matrices","k":"2","x":"Row·column rule · Shapes that conform · Matrix as a linear transformation of space · Composition of transforms · Cost: O(n³) for n×n","s":"A matrix is a machine that takes a vector in and spits a transformed vector out — rotating, stretching, or squishing space. Every layer of a neural net is one such transformation, so a 'forward pass' is just matrix × vector, over and over."},{"f":"2.5","t":"Transpose, Identity, Hadamard & Broadcasting","tn":"Linear Algebra I — Vectors & Matrices","k":"2","x":"Transpose and (AB)ᵀ=BᵀAᵀ · Identity & zero matrices · Element-wise (Hadamard) product · NumPy broadcasting rules · Bias add as broadcasting","s":"These are the everyday tools of array math: flipping a matrix (transpose), the do-nothing matrix (identity), multiplying element-by-element (Hadamard), and the auto-stretching that lets you add one bias to a whole batch at once (broadcasting)."},{"f":"2.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Linear Algebra I — Vectors & Matrices","k":"2","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"3.1","t":"Systems of Equations & Gaussian Elimination","tn":"Linear Algebra II — Systems, Spaces & Rank","k":"3","x":"Linear systems as Ax=b · Row operations · Row echelon form · Back-substitution · Consistent vs inconsistent systems","s":"Solving Ax = b means finding the inputs that produce a wanted output, and Gaussian elimination is the tidy bookkeeping that cracks it — the same kind of problem you solve when fitting a line to data."},{"f":"3.2","t":"Rank, Column Space & Null Space","tn":"Linear Algebra II — Systems, Spaces & Rank","k":"3","x":"Column space = reachable outputs · Null space = directions that vanish · Rank as number of independent directions · Rank–nullity theorem · Full vs low rank","s":"Rank counts how many genuinely independent directions a matrix carries — how much real information is inside it. It's why LoRA can fine-tune a giant model cheaply: the change it needs is low-rank, only a few directions."},{"f":"3.3","t":"Linear Independence, Basis & Dimension","tn":"Linear Algebra II — Systems, Spaces & Rank","k":"3","x":"Independence · Basis = minimal spanning set · Dimension · Coordinates in a basis · Change of basis","s":"A basis is a minimal set of directions you can build everything else from — like primary colors for space. Embedding dimensions are a learned basis for meaning: a few hundred directions that mix to represent any word."},{"f":"3.4","t":"Orthogonality, Projections & Gram–Schmidt","tn":"Linear Algebra II — Systems, Spaces & Rank","k":"3","x":"Orthogonal & orthonormal sets · Projection onto a subspace · Least-squares as projection · Gram–Schmidt process · Orthogonal matrices preserve length","s":"Two vectors are orthogonal (a right angle) when they share nothing — their dot product is zero. 'Projecting' finds the closest point in a subspace, which is exactly what least-squares does: the best fit is the shadow of the data on the model."},{"f":"3.5","t":"QR Decomposition","tn":"Linear Algebra II — Systems, Spaces & Rank","k":"3","x":"A = QR · Q orthonormal, R upper-triangular · Solving least-squares with QR · Numerical advantage over normal equations · Connection to Gram–Schmidt","s":"QR splits a matrix into a clean rotation (Q) and a simple triangle (R). It's the numerically trustworthy way to fit linear regression — the same answer as the textbook formula, but without the round-off errors that formula quietly builds up."},{"f":"3.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Linear Algebra II — Systems, Spaces & Rank","k":"3","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"4.1","t":"Vector Norms (L1, L2, L∞, Lp)","tn":"Linear Algebra III — Norms, Distances & Inverses","k":"4","x":"What a norm measures · L2 (Euclidean), L1 (taxicab), L∞ (max) · Unit balls of each norm · Sparsity of L1 · Lp family","s":"A norm is a ruler for how 'big' a vector is — and different rulers care about different things. The L2 ruler shrinks big values; the L1 ruler pushes values to exactly zero, which is why L1 gives you sparse, mostly-zero weights."},{"f":"4.2","t":"Matrix Norms (Frobenius, Spectral)","tn":"Linear Algebra III — Norms, Distances & Inverses","k":"4","x":"Frobenius norm · Spectral (operator) norm · Norms as bounds on amplification · Lipschitz constant of a layer · Spectral normalization","s":"A matrix norm measures how much a transformation can amplify a vector — its maximum gain. Keeping that gain in check (spectral normalization) is how you stop a network's signals from exploding, and it's key to stable GAN training."},{"f":"4.3","t":"Matrix Inverse & Pseudo-inverse","tn":"Linear Algebra III — Norms, Distances & Inverses","k":"4","x":"When an inverse exists · Singular vs invertible · Moore–Penrose pseudo-inverse · Why we rarely form inverses · Solve, don't invert","s":"The inverse 'undoes' a matrix, and the pseudo-inverse does its best when a true undo is impossible. The practical lesson: you almost never actually compute an inverse — you 'solve,' which is faster and far more stable."},{"f":"4.4","t":"Solving Ax=b, LU & Numerical Stability","tn":"Linear Algebra III — Norms, Distances & Inverses","k":"4","x":"LU decomposition · Forward/back substitution · Condition number · Catastrophic cancellation · Why stability matters in training","s":"LU factorization turns one hard solve into two easy triangular ones. The deeper idea is the 'condition number': some problems magnify tiny errors enormously, and knowing when you're in that danger zone separates working code from code that quietly returns garbage."},{"f":"4.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Linear Algebra III — Norms, Distances & Inverses","k":"4","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"5.1","t":"Eigenvalues & Eigenvectors","tn":"Linear Algebra IV — Eigenvalues, PCA & SVD","k":"5","x":"Directions a matrix only stretches · Characteristic equation det(A−λI)=0 · Computing eigenpairs · Geometric meaning · Repeated & complex eigenvalues","s":"An eigenvector is a special direction a matrix only stretches (never rotates), and its eigenvalue is by how much. They reveal a matrix's natural axes — and the eigenvalues of the loss's curvature tell you which directions are steep and which are flat."},{"f":"5.2","t":"Diagonalization & Symmetric Matrices","tn":"Linear Algebra IV — Eigenvalues, PCA & SVD","k":"5","x":"A = PDP⁻¹ · Powers of a matrix · Symmetric ⇒ real eigenvalues & orthogonal eigenvectors · Spectral theorem · Orthogonal diagonalization","s":"Diagonalizing means finding a matrix's natural axes so it becomes pure stretching, no rotation. Symmetric matrices — like every covariance matrix — always have perfectly perpendicular axes, the mathematical gift that makes PCA work."},{"f":"5.3","t":"Positive Definite Matrices","tn":"Linear Algebra IV — Eigenvalues, PCA & SVD","k":"5","x":"xᵀAx > 0 · Tests for positive definiteness · Cholesky factor · Connection to convexity · PSD covariance & kernels","s":"A positive-definite matrix curves upward like a bowl in every direction. That's the exact condition for a real minimum (not a saddle), and it's what makes covariance matrices and kernels so well-behaved."},{"f":"5.4","t":"Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)","tn":"Linear Algebra IV — Eigenvalues, PCA & SVD","k":"5","x":"A = UΣVᵀ for any matrix · Full derivation from AᵀA · Singular values vs eigenvalues · Geometric picture: rotate–stretch–rotate · Rank from singular values","s":"SVD says any matrix — any transformation at all — is just a rotation, then a stretch along clean axes, then another rotation. It's the Swiss-army knife of linear algebra: compression, recommendations, and low-rank adapters all fall out of it."},{"f":"5.5","t":"PCA from SVD & Low-Rank Approximation","tn":"Linear Algebra IV — Eigenvalues, PCA & SVD","k":"5","x":"Centering data · Principal components = top singular directions · Variance explained · Eckart–Young low-rank theorem · Reconstruction error","s":"PCA finds the few directions your data actually spreads along and throws the rest away — keeping the shape while using far fewer numbers. It's lossy compression with a proof that it's the best compression of its size."},{"f":"5.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Linear Algebra IV — Eigenvalues, PCA & SVD","k":"5","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"6.1","t":"Limits, Continuity & the Derivative","tn":"Calculus I — Derivatives & Gradients","k":"6","x":"Limits as 'getting arbitrarily close' · Continuity intuitively · Derivative as slope and as rate · The difference quotient · Differentiable ⇒ continuous","s":"A derivative is just the slope — how fast something changes at a point. Learning needs slopes: a model feels which way is downhill on its error and steps that way, so 'smooth enough to have a slope' is a requirement, not a nicety."},{"f":"6.2","t":"Differentiation Rules & the Chain Rule","tn":"Calculus I — Derivatives & Gradients","k":"6","x":"Power, product, quotient rules · The chain rule · Derivatives of exp, log, sigmoid · Composing rules · Why the chain rule is backprop","s":"The chain rule gives the slope of nested functions by multiplying the slopes of each layer. That's the whole engine of deep learning — backpropagation is literally the chain rule applied from the output back to every weight."},{"f":"6.3","t":"Partial Derivatives & the Gradient","tn":"Calculus I — Derivatives & Gradients","k":"6","x":"Partial derivatives · The gradient vector · Why the gradient points uphill · Directional derivatives · Gradient of a dot product / quadratic","s":"When a function has many inputs, the gradient is the arrow pointing in the steepest-uphill direction. Training walks the opposite way, downhill, one small step at a time. Every model that ever learned anything did it by following this arrow."},{"f":"6.4","t":"Jacobian & Hessian","tn":"Calculus I — Derivatives & Gradients","k":"6","x":"Jacobian of a vector function · Chain rule with Jacobians · Second derivatives · The Hessian matrix · Curvature and definiteness","s":"The Jacobian is the gradient's big brother for functions with many outputs — a whole table of slopes — and the Hessian is the curvature, how the slope itself bends. Backprop multiplies Jacobians; curvature tells you how big a step is safe."},{"f":"6.5","t":"Taylor Expansion (1st & 2nd order)","tn":"Calculus I — Derivatives & Gradients","k":"6","x":"Linear approximation · Quadratic approximation · Remainder term · Multivariate Taylor · Approximating the loss locally","s":"A Taylor expansion approximates any curvy function nearby with a simple line or parabola — zoom in far enough and everything looks straight. Gradient descent is exactly what you get by trusting that straight-line view for one small step."},{"f":"6.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Calculus I — Derivatives & Gradients","k":"6","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"7.1","t":"Antiderivatives & the Definite Integral","tn":"Calculus II — Integration & Expectation","k":"7","x":"Integral as accumulated area · Riemann sums · Antiderivatives · Notation and bounds · Signed area","s":"An integral adds up infinitely many tiny slices to get a total — usually the area under a curve. In probability it's how a 'density' becomes an actual probability, since the whole area under a distribution must add to 1."},{"f":"7.2","t":"Fundamental Theorem of Calculus","tn":"Calculus II — Integration & Expectation","k":"7","x":"Differentiation and integration are inverses · FTC part I & II · Evaluating definite integrals · Why it matters · Worked examples","s":"This is the theorem that integration and differentiation are opposites — each undoes the other. It's why, if you know how fast probability piles up (the density), you can integrate to get the running total (the CDF), and vice versa."},{"f":"7.3","t":"Substitution & Integration by Parts","tn":"Calculus II — Integration & Expectation","k":"7","x":"u-substitution · Integration by parts · Choosing u and dv · Definite-integral substitution · Common ML integrals","s":"These are the two moves for harder integrals: cleverly rename a variable (substitution) or trade one integral for an easier one (by parts). That 'change of variables' idea is the same one behind the reparameterization trick and normalizing flows."},{"f":"7.4","t":"The Gaussian Integral","tn":"Calculus II — Integration & Expectation","k":"7","x":"∫e^{−x²}dx = √π via the polar trick · Normalizing the Normal distribution · Completing the square · Moments of the Gaussian · Multivariate normalization","s":"There's one famous bell-curve integral with a beautiful answer (√π), found by a slick polar-coordinate trick. It's the reason the Normal distribution has that 1/√(2π) out front — it's just the number that makes its total area equal 1."},{"f":"7.5","t":"Integrals as Expectation","tn":"Calculus II — Integration & Expectation","k":"7","x":"E[X] as an integral · Law of the unconscious statistician · Expectation of functions · Variance as an integral · Monte-Carlo estimation","s":"An 'expectation' is a weighted average, written as an integral — and it's quietly the most important idea in ML: the loss you truly want to minimize is an average over all data, which training approximates by averaging over minibatches."},{"f":"7.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Calculus II — Integration & Expectation","k":"7","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"8.1","t":"Minima, Maxima & Saddle Points","tn":"Optimization Theory","k":"8","x":"Critical points · First-order condition ∇f=0 · Second-order test · Saddle points in high dimensions · Why deep nets have many saddles","s":"At the bottom of a valley the slope is zero — but so is the top of a hill and a 'saddle' (up one way, down another). In the millions of dimensions of a neural net, the places training stalls are almost always saddles, not bad valleys."},{"f":"8.2","t":"Convexity","tn":"Optimization Theory","k":"8","x":"Convex sets & functions · The chord-above-graph test · Second-derivative test for convexity · Global vs local minima · Convex losses (logistic, linear)","s":"A convex function is a single smooth bowl: wherever you start, downhill leads to the one true bottom. When your loss is convex (like logistic regression), optimization is stress-free — there are no bad local minima to fear."},{"f":"8.3","t":"Gradient Descent from Taylor Expansion","tn":"Optimization Theory","k":"8","x":"Derive the update from a 1st-order model · Learning-rate intuition · Steepest descent direction · Convergence on convex functions · Step-size pitfalls","s":"Gradient descent isn't a guess — it falls out of the math: approximate the loss by a line, and 'step downhill' is provably the best move. This one update, with the gradient estimated on a minibatch, is how essentially every model trains."},{"f":"8.4","t":"Momentum & Adam","tn":"Optimization Theory","k":"8","x":"Momentum as a heavy ball · RMSProp scaling · Adam = momentum + adaptive scale · Bias correction · Why Adam is the default","s":"Plain gradient descent zig-zags; momentum gives it a heavy ball's inertia so it rolls smoothly, and Adam adds a custom step size for every parameter. Adam is the optimizer training most of the models you've heard of."},{"f":"8.5","t":"Lagrange Multipliers & KKT","tn":"Optimization Theory","k":"8","x":"Constrained optimization · Lagrange multipliers · Equality vs inequality constraints · KKT conditions · Duality (intro)","s":"When you must optimize under a constraint ('do your best, but stay on this line'), Lagrange multipliers turn it back into an ordinary problem. It's the machinery behind support vector machines and the KL 'leash' that keeps RLHF models in line."},{"f":"8.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Optimization Theory","k":"8","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"9.1","t":"Sample Spaces, Events & Axioms","tn":"Probability I — Foundations","k":"9","x":"Sample space & events · Kolmogorov axioms · Union, intersection, complement · Inclusion–exclusion · Equally-likely outcomes","s":"Probability starts by listing everything that could happen (the sample space) and giving each outcome a share that all add to 1. Three simple rules are the whole foundation — everything else is built from them."},{"f":"9.2","t":"Conditional Probability & Independence","tn":"Probability I — Foundations","k":"9","x":"P(A|B) definition · Multiplication rule · Independence · Conditional independence · Chain rule of probability","s":"Conditional probability is 'given that this happened, how likely is that?' — updating your belief on new information. A language model is built from exactly this: it predicts each next word given all the words so far."},{"f":"9.3","t":"Bayes' Theorem","tn":"Probability I — Foundations","k":"9","x":"Prior, likelihood, posterior · Full derivation · Law of total probability · Base-rate intuition · Naive Bayes","s":"Bayes' theorem is the formula for changing your mind with evidence: start with a prior belief, see data, get an updated belief. It's one line of algebra, and it underlies spam filters, medical tests, and Bayesian deep learning alike."},{"f":"9.4","t":"Random Variables, Expectation & Variance","tn":"Probability I — Foundations","k":"9","x":"Discrete random variables · PMFs · Expected value · Variance & standard deviation · Linearity of expectation","s":"A random variable is a number whose value is uncertain. Its 'expectation' is the long-run average you'd get, and its 'variance' is how much it jumps around. Training a model is, at heart, minimizing an expected value."},{"f":"9.5","t":"Covariance, Correlation & Joint Distributions","tn":"Probability I — Foundations","k":"9","x":"Joint, marginal, conditional · Covariance · Correlation · Independence vs uncorrelated · Covariance matrix","s":"Covariance measures whether two quantities move together. Pack all the pairwise covariances into a matrix and you get the object at the heart of PCA, whitening, and every Gaussian model — a compact summary of how your features relate."},{"f":"9.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Probability I — Foundations","k":"9","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"10.1","t":"PDFs, CDFs & the Uniform","tn":"Probability II — Continuous Distributions & Theorems","k":"10","x":"Density vs probability · PDF integrates to 1 · CDF and quantiles · Uniform distribution · Sampling via inverse CDF","s":"For continuous things, probability lives in a 'density' — the height of a curve — and you get real probabilities by measuring area under it. The humble uniform (equally-likely) distribution is the raw randomness that seeds dropout and shuffling."},{"f":"10.2","t":"The Gaussian (Normal) Distribution","tn":"Probability II — Continuous Distributions & Theorems","k":"10","x":"The bell curve · Mean & variance · Standardization (z-scores) · 68–95–99.7 rule · Why Gaussians are everywhere (CLT preview)","s":"The bell curve is the default shape of randomness in nature and in ML. Just two numbers — its center and its spread — describe it completely, and carefully-scaled Gaussians are how a network's weights are first born."},{"f":"10.3","t":"Exponential, Beta & Dirichlet","tn":"Probability II — Continuous Distributions & Theorems","k":"10","x":"Exponential (waiting times) · Beta on [0,1] · Dirichlet over simplices · Conjugacy · Use in topic models","s":"A small zoo of handy distributions: the exponential for waiting times, the Beta for a probability that is itself uncertain, and the Dirichlet for a whole set of probabilities that must sum to 1 (like a mix of topics)."},{"f":"10.4","t":"The Multivariate Gaussian","tn":"Probability II — Continuous Distributions & Theorems","k":"10","x":"Mean vector & covariance matrix · Contours as ellipses · Whitening · Marginals & conditionals · Log-density","s":"The bell curve in many dimensions — a fuzzy ellipsoidal cloud described by a center and a covariance matrix. The latent space of a VAE and the whole idea of a Gaussian process live inside this one distribution."},{"f":"10.5","t":"Change of Variables & the Reparameterization Trick","tn":"Probability II — Continuous Distributions & Theorems","k":"10","x":"Density under a transform · Jacobian determinant · z = μ + σ·ε · Why it enables backprop through sampling · Normalizing flows (preview)","s":"When you transform a random variable, its density stretches and squishes by the Jacobian. The reparameterization trick uses this to write randomness as 'mean + noise × spread' — the clever move that lets a VAE learn through a random step."},{"f":"10.6","t":"Law of Large Numbers & CLT","tn":"Probability II — Continuous Distributions & Theorems","k":"10","x":"Sample mean converges · LLN statement · Central Limit Theorem · Proof sketch via MGFs · Simulation","s":"The Law of Large Numbers says averages settle down as you gather more samples; the Central Limit Theorem says those averages turn bell-shaped. Together they're why a noisy minibatch gradient is still a trustworthy estimate of the true one."},{"f":"10.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Probability II — Continuous Distributions & Theorems","k":"10","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"11.1","t":"Point Estimation, Bias & Variance","tn":"Statistics & Estimation","k":"11","x":"Estimators · Bias of an estimator · Variance of an estimator · Mean squared error · Consistency","s":"An estimator is a recipe for guessing an unknown number from data. 'Bias' is how wrong it is on average; 'variance' is how much it wobbles from run to run. A model's error splits neatly into exactly these pieces, plus unavoidable noise."},{"f":"11.2","t":"Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE)","tn":"Statistics & Estimation","k":"11","x":"Likelihood vs probability · Log-likelihood · MLE for Bernoulli, Gaussian, Categorical · Why we maximize log · MLE = minimizing cross-entropy","s":"Maximum likelihood picks the parameters that make your observed data look most likely — 'whatever explains what I saw best.' The punchline: the cross-entropy loss you train classifiers with is exactly this, in disguise."},{"f":"11.3","t":"MAP Estimation & Priors","tn":"Statistics & Estimation","k":"11","x":"Adding a prior · Posterior ∝ likelihood × prior · MAP derivation · Gaussian prior ⇒ L2 · Laplace prior ⇒ L1","s":"MAP is maximum likelihood with an opinion added — a prior belief about the answer before you see data. A 'weights should be small' prior gives you L2 regularization for free; a 'weights should be sparse' prior gives L1."},{"f":"11.4","t":"The Bias–Variance Tradeoff","tn":"Statistics & Estimation","k":"11","x":"Decomposing expected error · Underfitting vs overfitting · Model capacity · Formal derivation · Double descent (note)","s":"Too simple a model misses the pattern (bias); too complex a model memorizes the noise (variance). The whole art of ML is balancing the two — and this one curve is why model size and regularization matter so much."},{"f":"11.5","t":"Hypothesis Testing, CIs & Bootstrap","tn":"Statistics & Estimation","k":"11","x":"Null & alternative · p-values (correctly) · Confidence intervals · The bootstrap · A/B testing models","s":"This is the toolkit for asking 'is this real, or just luck?' — p-values, confidence intervals, and the bootstrap (re-sampling your data to feel out uncertainty). Comparing two models' scores honestly is exactly this kind of test."},{"f":"11.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Statistics & Estimation","k":"11","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"12.1","t":"Entropy","tn":"Information Theory","k":"12","x":"Surprise = −log p · Entropy as average surprise · Derivation & units (bits/nats) · Max-entropy distributions · Entropy of Bernoulli","s":"Entropy measures surprise — how uncertain an outcome is, in bits. A fair coin is 1 bit; a loaded one is less. A language model's 'perplexity' is just its entropy dressed up: how many equally-likely choices it feels it's guessing among."},{"f":"12.2","t":"Cross-Entropy & KL Divergence","tn":"Information Theory","k":"12","x":"Cross-entropy H(p,q) · KL divergence · Why KL ≥ 0 (Gibbs) · Why KL is asymmetric · Cross-entropy = entropy + KL","s":"Cross-entropy is how many extra bits you waste when your predicted distribution is wrong; KL divergence is that waste itself — the gap between two distributions. Training a classifier is literally shrinking this gap to the true labels."},{"f":"12.3","t":"Mutual Information","tn":"Information Theory","k":"12","x":"Information shared by two variables · MI = H(X)−H(X|Y) · Non-negativity · Estimation difficulties · InfoNCE (preview)","s":"Mutual information measures how much knowing one thing tells you about another — shared information, in bits. It's zero for unrelated things, and maximizing it is the quiet goal behind contrastive self-supervised learning."},{"f":"12.4","t":"Jensen's Inequality & the ELBO","tn":"Information Theory","k":"12","x":"Convexity and expectations · Jensen's inequality · Bits vs nats recap · Deriving the ELBO · Information gain in trees","s":"Jensen's inequality is a simple fact about curves that lets you swap an impossible calculation for a solvable lower bound. That bound — the ELBO — is the exact objective a VAE trains on, so this small inequality powers modern generative models."},{"f":"12.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Information Theory","k":"12","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"13.1","t":"Floating Point & Rounding Error","tn":"Numerical Methods & Computational Math","k":"13","x":"IEEE 754 floats · float32 vs float16 vs bfloat16 · Machine epsilon · Rounding error accumulation · Representable range","s":"Computers can't store most numbers exactly — they round. Knowing where those tiny errors hide (and why bfloat16 trades precision for range) is what lets you train huge models without them silently blowing up or grinding to zero."},{"f":"13.2","t":"Numerical Stability & Log-Sum-Exp","tn":"Numerical Methods & Computational Math","k":"13","x":"Catastrophic cancellation · Overflow/underflow in softmax · The log-sum-exp trick · Stable cross-entropy · Subtracting the max","s":"Some correct formulas give wrong answers on a computer because they overflow or cancel catastrophically. The log-sum-exp trick — subtract the max first — is the classic fix, and it's why every softmax you've ever used quietly subtracts a constant."},{"f":"13.3","t":"Matrix Factorizations in Practice","tn":"Numerical Methods & Computational Math","k":"13","x":"LU vs Cholesky vs QR · When to use which · Cost comparison · Conditioning · Solvers under the hood","s":"LU, Cholesky, and QR are three ways to break a matrix apart to solve problems fast and stably. This is the practical 'which tool when' guide — the judgment that keeps linear-algebra code both quick and correct."},{"f":"13.4","t":"Automatic Differentiation (Forward vs Reverse)","tn":"Numerical Methods & Computational Math","k":"13","x":"Dual numbers (forward mode) · The computational graph · Reverse mode = backprop · Why reverse is O(1)× the forward cost · VJPs","s":"Autodiff is how frameworks get exact gradients automatically, with no hand calculus. The key insight: computing all the gradients backward costs about the same as one forward pass — the entire reason training deep nets is affordable."},{"f":"13.5","t":"Gradient Checking & Mixed Precision","tn":"Numerical Methods & Computational Math","k":"13","x":"Finite-difference gradients · Checking analytic gradients · Relative error · Mixed-precision training · Loss scaling","s":"Gradient checking is the cheap sanity test — compare your gradient to a nudge-and-measure estimate — that catches backprop bugs instantly. Mixed precision is doing the heavy math in 16 bits to train faster without losing accuracy."},{"f":"13.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Numerical Methods & Computational Math","k":"13","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"14.1","t":"Gradients, Jacobians & the Shape Rule","tn":"Matrix Calculus & Backpropagation","k":"14","x":"Scalar vs vector vs matrix derivatives · The gradient and the Jacobian · The shape rule · Finite-difference gradient checks","s":"When you take derivatives with vectors and matrices, the only real trick is bookkeeping: the gradient always has the same shape as the thing you differentiated. Nail that one rule and matrix calculus stops being scary."},{"f":"14.2","t":"Differentiating Vector & Matrix Expressions","tn":"Matrix Calculus & Backpropagation","k":"14","x":"The core identities (aᵀx, xᵀAx, …) · Index-notation derivations · Least squares & the normal equations · Trace and Frobenius derivatives","s":"A small handful of patterns (like 'the derivative of aᵀx is a') covers almost every gradient in ML. Learn them the way you learned 'the derivative of x² is 2x' — by recognizing the shape, not re-deriving each time."},{"f":"14.3","t":"The Vector Chain Rule & Jacobians","tn":"Matrix Calculus & Backpropagation","k":"14","x":"Composing Jacobians · Vector–Jacobian products (VJPs) · Reverse vs forward mode · Why backprop costs about one forward pass","s":"The chain rule for vectors is just multiplying each layer's sensitivity table (its Jacobian) together. Do that multiplication starting from the output and you get backprop — which is why one backward pass produces every gradient at once."},{"f":"14.4","t":"Backprop Through a Linear Layer","tn":"Matrix Calculus & Backpropagation","k":"14","x":"Deriving dW, db, dX · The input-times-error pattern · Summing the bias over the batch · Stacking layers into a network","s":"Deriving the gradients of a single dense layer by hand is the moment backprop clicks: a weight's gradient is simply its input times the incoming error. See it once here and you can read the backward pass of any network."},{"f":"14.5","t":"The Softmax + Cross-Entropy Gradient","tn":"Matrix Calculus & Backpropagation","k":"14","x":"The softmax Jacobian · The clean p − y result · Numerical stability (log-sum-exp) · Link to logistic regression","s":"Softmax and cross-entropy look messy alone, but together their gradient collapses to the most elegant result in ML: predicted minus target, 'p − y.' It's why the two are always paired, and why every classifier's output layer is so clean."},{"f":"14.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Matrix Calculus & Backpropagation","k":"14","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"15.1","t":"Conjugate Priors & Bayesian Updating","tn":"Bayesian Inference & Probabilistic ML","k":"15","x":"Bayes' rule for parameters · Beta–Bernoulli conjugacy · Posterior = prior + data · Credible intervals & pseudo-counts","s":"Bayesian updating means holding a belief as a whole distribution and sharpening it with each new data point. In the lucky 'conjugate' case, updating is pure arithmetic — you just add your heads and tails to the prior's counts."},{"f":"15.2","t":"Bayesian Linear Regression","tn":"Bayesian Inference & Probabilistic ML","k":"15","x":"Gaussian posterior over weights · Precision = prior + data · Predictive uncertainty (noise + weights) · Ridge regression as MAP","s":"Instead of one best-fit line, keep every plausible line and see how much they disagree. The payoff is honest error bars that grow wide exactly where you have no data — a model that knows what it doesn't know."},{"f":"15.3","t":"MCMC: Metropolis–Hastings","tn":"Bayesian Inference & Probabilistic ML","k":"15","x":"Sampling unnormalized posteriors · The acceptance ratio · Detailed balance · Burn-in & mixing","s":"When the answer is a distribution too complicated to write down, MCMC draws samples from it anyway — using only its shape, never its impossible-to-compute total. It's a guided random walk that visits each region as often as it's probable."},{"f":"15.4","t":"Variational Inference & the ELBO","tn":"Bayesian Inference & Probabilistic ML","k":"15","x":"Inference as optimization · log p(x) = ELBO + KL · The reparameterization trick · The VAE objective","s":"Instead of chasing an impossible distribution exactly, pick a simple stand-in and tune it to fit as closely as possible. The quantity you maximize to do that — the ELBO — is exactly the loss that trains a VAE."},{"f":"15.5","t":"Gaussian Processes","tn":"Bayesian Inference & Probabilistic ML","k":"15","x":"A prior over functions · The kernel · GP regression posterior · Uncertainty that grows away from data","s":"A Gaussian process puts a probability distribution over whole functions, not just numbers. Feed it a few points and it returns a smooth best-guess curve plus a shaded band of uncertainty that swells wherever data is sparse."},{"f":"15.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Bayesian Inference & Probabilistic ML","k":"15","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"16.1","t":"Variational Autoencoders (VAEs)","tn":"Diffusion & Generative Models","k":"16","x":"The ELBO as encoder + decoder · Reconstruction + KL · The reparameterization trick · Latent-space generation","s":"A VAE squeezes data down to a small 'latent code' and learns to rebuild it — while keeping those codes shaped like a simple bell curve. That last part is the magic: afterward you can draw a random code and decode brand-new data."},{"f":"16.2","t":"GANs: Generation as a Game","tn":"Diffusion & Generative Models","k":"16","x":"The min–max objective · Optimal discriminator · Jensen–Shannon divergence · Mode collapse & instability","s":"A GAN is a forger and a detective locked in competition: the generator makes fakes, the discriminator tries to catch them, and each pushes the other to improve. When the detective can only guess, the fakes have become indistinguishable from real."},{"f":"16.3","t":"The Forward Diffusion Process","tn":"Diffusion & Generative Models","k":"16","x":"Fixed Gaussian noising · The closed form q(x_t|x₀) · Noise schedules · Data → N(0,I)","s":"Take a clean image and slowly stir in noise until it's pure static — that's the (unlearned) forward process. One tidy formula lets you jump straight to any noise level, which is what makes training a diffusion model practical."},{"f":"16.4","t":"Score Matching & Denoising","tn":"Diffusion & Generative Models","k":"16","x":"The score ∇log p(x) · Denoising = score matching · The DDPM ε-prediction loss · Tweedie's formula","s":"To reverse the noise, a network learns to look at a fuzzy point and say 'the clean data was that way.' Astonishingly, learning to denoise is the same as learning the 'score' — the field of arrows pointing toward where real data lives."},{"f":"16.5","t":"The Reverse Process & Sampling","tn":"Diffusion & Generative Models","k":"16","x":"Langevin dynamics · Annealed sampling · Reverse diffusion (DDPM) · The MCMC connection","s":"Generation is running the noise backward: start from static and repeatedly nudge toward data along the learned arrows, with a dash of randomness. It's the exact same 'follow the gradient' idea as MCMC — now painting images."},{"f":"16.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Diffusion & Generative Models","k":"16","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"17.1","t":"Depth, Nonlinearity & Gradient Flow","tn":"Neural-Network & Transformer Math","k":"17","x":"Why nonlinearity matters · Activation derivatives · Vanishing/exploding gradients · ReLU, GELU, dead units","s":"Stack straight lines and you still get a straight line, so the 'kinks' between layers (activations) are what make depth powerful. But those same kinks decide whether the learning signal survives the trip back — the whole vanishing-gradient story."},{"f":"17.2","t":"Convolution as Matrix Multiply","tn":"Neural-Network & Transformer Math","k":"17","x":"Locality & weight sharing · im2col · Parameter count vs dense · Translation equivariance","s":"A convolution is a dense layer with two rules baked in: only look at a small patch, and reuse the same weights everywhere. Those two constraints are the entire 'vision' inductive bias — and they run as a plain matrix multiply."},{"f":"17.3","t":"Normalization: BatchNorm & LayerNorm","tn":"Neural-Network & Transformer Math","k":"17","x":"Normalize then affine (γ, β) · Batch vs feature axis · Why LayerNorm for transformers · The backward pass","s":"As numbers flow through a deep net they drift in scale and destabilize training. Normalization re-centers them at each layer; the only difference between the two flavors is which direction you average over, and LayerNorm's choice is why transformers use it."},{"f":"17.4","t":"Attention: The QKV Mechanism","tn":"Neural-Network & Transformer Math","k":"17","x":"Query, key, value · softmax(QKᵀ/√d)·V · Why the √d scaling · Self-attention","s":"Attention lets every word ask a question and gather answers from every other word, weighted by relevance — a soft, content-based lookup across the whole sentence. It's the single mechanism at the heart of every transformer."},{"f":"17.5","t":"Multi-Head Attention & the Transformer Block","tn":"Neural-Network & Transformer Math","k":"17","x":"Multiple heads · Residual + LayerNorm + MLP · The full block · Parameter & FLOP counts","s":"Run several attentions in parallel (each watching for a different kind of relationship), then wrap attention and a small network in the 'add-the-input-back' trick and normalization. Stack that block dozens of times and you have GPT."},{"f":"17.E","t":"Track Exam","tn":"Neural-Network & Transformer Math","k":"17","x":"","s":"Track Exam"},{"f":"C.1","t":"PCA from Scratch on MNIST","tn":"Capstones — Projects That Run","k":"C","x":"Implement PCA with only NumPy · Apply to MNIST digits · Visualize the top-16 principal components · Variance explained curve · Reconstruct digits from k components","s":"Build PCA with nothing but NumPy and watch it squeeze 64-pixel digits down to a handful of numbers — then rebuild them. Real compression, from the eigenvectors up, running live in your browser."},{"f":"C.2","t":"Gradient Descent, Momentum & Adam","tn":"Capstones — Projects That Run","k":"C","x":"Implement GD, momentum, Adam from scratch · Non-convex 2-D loss surface · Compare convergence · Animate the trajectories · Effect of learning rate","s":"Code all three optimizers by hand and race them across a tricky valley, seeing exactly why momentum and Adam beat plain gradient descent. After this, your optimizer is no longer a black box."},{"f":"C.3","t":"A Bayesian Classifier from Scratch","tn":"Capstones — Projects That Run","k":"C","x":"Gaussian Naive Bayes · Derive the decision boundary · MLE vs MAP as data grows · Posterior probabilities · Compare to logistic regression","s":"Build a classifier that learns what each class 'looks like' and uses Bayes' rule to decide — then watch a good prior rescue it when data is scarce. The whole generative-vs-discriminative story in one runnable project."},{"f":"C.4","t":"Cross-Entropy, KL & Mutual Information","tn":"Capstones — Projects That Run","k":"C","x":"Compute CE, KL, MI for a tiny LM · Verify CE = H + KL numerically · Perplexity · MI between tokens · Bits vs nats in practice","s":"Build a tiny language model and measure it with the very quantities that train GPT — cross-entropy, KL, perplexity, mutual information — proving the famous identity CE = H + KL with real numbers."},{"f":"C.5","t":"A Tiny Autograd Engine","tn":"Capstones — Projects That Run","k":"C","x":"Reverse-mode AD from scratch · Scalar Value class with backward() · Verify against finite differences · Train a 2-layer MLP · Visualize the loss curve","s":"Build the core of PyTorch — a reverse-mode autograd engine — in about 40 lines, check it against finite differences, then train a real 2-layer network with it. After this, loss.backward() is never magic again."}],"glossary":[{"term":"Eigenvector","desc":"A nonzero vector v that a matrix A only stretches, never rotates: Av = λv. The scalar λ is its eigenvalue (the stretch factor), so eigenvectors are a matrix's natural axes."},{"term":"Eigenvalue","desc":"The scalar λ by which a matrix stretches its eigenvector: Av = λv. Found by solving the characteristic equation det(A − λI) = 0."},{"term":"Characteristic equation","desc":"det(A − λI) = 0. Its roots are the eigenvalues of the matrix A."},{"term":"Vector","desc":"An ordered list of numbers; geometrically an arrow with a direction and a length. A word embedding is a vector."},{"term":"Matrix","desc":"A rectangular grid of numbers that acts as a linear transformation of space. A dense neural-network layer's weights are a matrix."},{"term":"Scalar","desc":"A single number, as opposed to a vector, matrix, or tensor."},{"term":"Tensor","desc":"A multi-dimensional array (a batch of matrices); generalizes scalars, vectors, and matrices."},{"term":"Dot product","desc":"a·b = Σ aᵢbᵢ = ‖a‖‖b‖cos θ — one number measuring how much two vectors point the same way. An attention score is a dot product of a query and a key."},{"term":"Matrix multiplication","desc":"Combines two linear maps: AB applies B then A, by the row·column rule. Cost is O(n³) for n×n matrices."},{"term":"Transpose","desc":"Aᵀ swaps rows and columns; (AB)ᵀ = BᵀAᵀ."},{"term":"Norm","desc":"A vector's length. L2: ‖x‖₂ = √(Σ xᵢ²) (Euclidean); L1: Σ|xᵢ| (taxicab, encourages sparsity); L∞: max|xᵢ|."},{"term":"Determinant","desc":"det(A): the factor by which A scales area/volume. det = 0 means A collapses space and has no inverse."},{"term":"Rank","desc":"The number of independent directions in a matrix's output (the dimension of its column space). Low rank means redundancy — the idea behind LoRA."},{"term":"Null space","desc":"All vectors x with Ax = 0 — the directions a matrix flattens to zero."},{"term":"Column space","desc":"All vectors reachable as Ax — the outputs a matrix can actually produce."},{"term":"Basis","desc":"A minimal set of independent vectors that spans a space; every vector is a unique combination of them."},{"term":"Linear independence","desc":"A set of vectors is independent when none is a combination of the others (for a square matrix, det ≠ 0)."},{"term":"Span","desc":"The set of all linear combinations of a group of vectors."},{"term":"Orthogonal","desc":"Perpendicular: two vectors are orthogonal when their dot product is 0."},{"term":"Projection","desc":"The shadow of a vector onto a subspace — the closest point in it. The leftover error is orthogonal to the subspace, which is exactly least squares."},{"term":"Gram-Schmidt","desc":"A process that turns any independent vectors into an orthonormal set (perpendicular, unit length) spanning the same space."},{"term":"Inverse","desc":"A⁻¹ undoes A: A⁻¹A = I. It exists only when det(A) ≠ 0. In practice we solve Ax = b instead of forming A⁻¹."},{"term":"Pseudo-inverse","desc":"The Moore–Penrose inverse A⁺ that gives the least-squares solution when A isn't square or invertible."},{"term":"Condition number","desc":"How much a matrix amplifies input error. A large condition number means the matrix is ill-conditioned and solves are fragile."},{"term":"SVD","desc":"Singular Value Decomposition: every matrix factors as A = UΣVᵀ — rotate, then stretch by the singular values σ, then rotate. It powers PCA and low-rank compression."},{"term":"Singular value","desc":"The stretch factors σ along an SVD's axes. The largest singular value is the spectral norm ‖A‖₂."},{"term":"PCA","desc":"Principal Component Analysis: find the directions of greatest variance in data (the top eigenvectors of the covariance matrix / top singular directions) and keep only those to compress it."},{"term":"Diagonalization","desc":"Writing A = PDP⁻¹ with the eigenvalues on the diagonal of D; it makes matrix powers Aⁿ easy to compute."},{"term":"Positive definite","desc":"A symmetric matrix with xᵀAx > 0 for every x ≠ 0 (all eigenvalues positive). It signals a bowl-shaped minimum."},{"term":"Limit","desc":"The value a function approaches as its input gets arbitrarily close to a point; the foundation of the derivative."},{"term":"Derivative","desc":"f′(x): the slope of f at x — its instantaneous rate of change, the limit of (f(x+h) − f(x)) / h as h → 0."},{"term":"Partial derivative","desc":"The derivative with respect to one variable while holding the others fixed."},{"term":"Gradient","desc":"∇f: the vector of all partial derivatives. It points in the direction of steepest increase, so training steps the opposite way, along −∇f (downhill)."},{"term":"Chain rule","desc":"(f∘g)′ = f′(g(x))·g′(x). Backpropagation is the chain rule applied layer by layer."},{"term":"Jacobian","desc":"The matrix of all first partial derivatives of a vector-valued function: Jᵢⱼ = ∂fᵢ/∂xⱼ."},{"term":"Hessian","desc":"The matrix of second partial derivatives; it describes curvature. A positive-definite Hessian means a local minimum."},{"term":"Taylor expansion","desc":"Approximates a function near a point a by a polynomial: f(x) ≈ f(a) + f′(a)(x−a) + ½f″(a)(x−a)². Gradient descent comes straight from the first-order term."},{"term":"Integral","desc":"∫ f dx: the accumulated area under a curve — the reverse of differentiation (the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus)."},{"term":"Expectation","desc":"E[X] = Σ x·p(x) (or ∫ x·p(x) dx): the long-run average, the balance point of a distribution."},{"term":"Variance","desc":"Var(X) = E[(X − μ)²]: how spread out a distribution is. Its square root σ is the standard deviation."},{"term":"Covariance","desc":"Cov(X,Y) = E[(X−μₓ)(Y−μᵧ)]: how two variables move together. The covariance matrix collects all pairs and feeds PCA."},{"term":"Gradient descent","desc":"Repeatedly step downhill: x ← x − η·∇f(x), where η is the learning rate. It is the engine of training."},{"term":"Learning rate","desc":"η, the step size in gradient descent. Too large and it diverges; too small and it crawls."},{"term":"Momentum","desc":"Gradient descent with a running velocity (a heavy ball) so it accelerates along consistent directions and damps oscillation across a valley."},{"term":"Adam","desc":"The default deep-learning optimizer: momentum combined with per-parameter adaptive step sizes (RMSProp) and bias correction."},{"term":"SGD","desc":"Stochastic Gradient Descent: gradient descent where the gradient is estimated on a small random minibatch each step."},{"term":"Convex","desc":"A bowl-shaped function where every chord lies on or above the graph; it has a single global minimum (e.g. logistic and linear-regression losses)."},{"term":"Saddle point","desc":"A flat point (∇f = 0) that is a minimum in some directions and a maximum in others — not a true minimum. Common in deep networks."},{"term":"Lagrange multipliers","desc":"A method for constrained optimization: at the optimum the objective's gradient ∇f is parallel to the constraint's gradient ∇g."},{"term":"Probability","desc":"A number in [0,1] measuring how likely an event is; summed or integrated over all outcomes it equals 1."},{"term":"Conditional probability","desc":"P(A|B) = P(A∩B) / P(B): the probability of A once B is known."},{"term":"Independence","desc":"Two events are independent when P(A∩B) = P(A)·P(B) — knowing one tells you nothing about the other."},{"term":"Bayes' theorem","desc":"P(H|D) = P(D|H)·P(H) / P(D): update a prior belief with evidence to get a posterior. In short, posterior ∝ likelihood × prior."},{"term":"Prior","desc":"Your belief about a parameter before seeing data, P(H)."},{"term":"Posterior","desc":"Your updated belief after seeing data, P(H|D) ∝ likelihood × prior."},{"term":"Likelihood","desc":"P(D|H): how well a hypothesis explains the observed data."},{"term":"Random variable","desc":"A quantity whose value is set by chance, described by a PMF (discrete) or a PDF (continuous)."},{"term":"PDF","desc":"Probability density function p(x): area under it is probability, and it integrates to 1. Its running total is the CDF."},{"term":"CDF","desc":"Cumulative distribution function F(x) = P(X ≤ x): the area under the PDF up to x. Its slope is the density."},{"term":"Gaussian","desc":"The Normal 'bell curve' N(μ, σ²); about 68-95-99.7% of the mass lies within 1, 2, 3 standard deviations of the mean. It appears everywhere via the CLT."},{"term":"Central Limit Theorem","desc":"The average of many independent samples becomes Gaussian, no matter the shape of the original distribution."},{"term":"Law of Large Numbers","desc":"The average of more and more independent samples converges to the true mean — why minibatch gradients work."},{"term":"Reparameterization trick","desc":"Write a random draw as z = μ + σ·ε with ε ~ N(0,1), so gradients can flow through the sampling step. It's what lets a VAE train."},{"term":"MLE","desc":"Maximum Likelihood Estimation: choose the parameters that make the observed data most probable. It is equivalent to minimizing cross-entropy."},{"term":"MAP","desc":"Maximum A Posteriori: like MLE but with a prior — posterior ∝ likelihood × prior. A Gaussian prior gives L2 regularization; a Laplace prior gives L1."},{"term":"Bias-variance tradeoff","desc":"Expected test error = bias² + variance + noise. Too-simple models underfit (high bias); too-complex models overfit (high variance). The best fit is in between."},{"term":"Bias","desc":"For an estimator, how far its average prediction sits from the truth. Bias² is one term of test error."},{"term":"p-value","desc":"The probability, if the null hypothesis were true, of seeing a result at least as extreme as the one observed. Small p (say < 0.05) is taken as evidence against the null."},{"term":"Entropy","desc":"H = −Σ p·log p: the average surprise of a distribution, measured in bits or nats. It is largest for a uniform distribution."},{"term":"Cross-entropy","desc":"H(p,q) = −Σ p·log q: the bits you pay to encode the true distribution p using a model q. Classification training minimizes it."},{"term":"KL divergence","desc":"KL(p‖q) = Σ p·log(p/q) ≥ 0: the extra bits wasted by using q instead of the true p. Note cross-entropy = entropy + KL."},{"term":"Mutual information","desc":"I(X;Y) = H(X) − H(X|Y): how much knowing one variable reduces uncertainty about the other."},{"term":"Softmax","desc":"Turns a vector of scores into probabilities: softmax(x)ᵢ = eˣⁱ / Σⱼ eˣʲ. Subtract the max first for numerical stability."},{"term":"Jensen's inequality","desc":"For a convex function f, the average of f is at least f of the average: E[f(X)] ≥ f(E[X]). Its gap powers the ELBO."},{"term":"ELBO","desc":"Evidence Lower Bound: log p(x) = ELBO + KL, so maximizing the ELBO both fits the data and shrinks the KL. It is the training objective of a VAE."},{"term":"Log-sum-exp","desc":"A numerically stable way to compute log Σ eˣ by subtracting the max before exponentiating — it prevents overflow in softmax and cross-entropy."},{"term":"Floating point","desc":"How computers store real numbers approximately. The spacing between representable numbers doubles each power of two; float32/float16/bfloat16 trade precision for range."},{"term":"Automatic differentiation","desc":"Computing exact gradients by applying the chain rule over a computation graph. Reverse mode is backpropagation."},{"term":"Backpropagation","desc":"Reverse-mode autodiff: one forward pass computes the loss, then one backward pass multiplies local derivatives to produce every gradient — at about the cost of one forward pass."},{"term":"Convolution","desc":"A layer that slides a small shared kernel over the input (locality + weight sharing); it can be written as a single matrix multiply."},{"term":"BatchNorm","desc":"Normalizes activations across the batch to mean 0, variance 1, then rescales — stabilizes and speeds training."},{"term":"LayerNorm","desc":"Normalizes each token's own feature vector to mean 0, variance 1, then rescales (γ, β). It's the normalization used inside transformers."},{"term":"Residual connection","desc":"Adds a block's input to its output, x + f(x), so gradients flow cleanly and very deep networks can train."},{"term":"Activation function","desc":"The nonlinearity between layers (ReLU(x) = max(0,x), GELU, sigmoid). Without it, stacked layers would collapse into one linear map."},{"term":"Vanishing gradient","desc":"When gradients shrink toward zero through many layers (e.g. with sigmoids), stalling learning. ReLU/GELU and residual connections fix it."},{"term":"Attention","desc":"softmax(QKᵀ/√d)·V: each token forms a query, scores it against every key by dot product, and gathers a weighted sum of values. It is the core of the transformer."},{"term":"Query, key, value","desc":"In attention, the query asks a question, keys are matched against it (via dot product), and values are what gets gathered by the resulting weights."},{"term":"Multi-head attention","desc":"Running attention in several independent subspaces (heads) at once and concatenating them, so different heads can learn different relationships."},{"term":"Transformer","desc":"The architecture built from stacked blocks of multi-head attention + MLP with residual connections and LayerNorm — the basis of GPT and BERT."},{"term":"VAE","desc":"Variational Autoencoder: an encoder maps data to a distribution in latent space and a decoder reconstructs it, trained by maximizing the ELBO."},{"term":"GAN","desc":"Generative Adversarial Network: a generator and a discriminator play a min–max game until the generator's samples are indistinguishable from real data."},{"term":"Diffusion model","desc":"A generative model that slowly adds Gaussian noise to data (forward process) and learns to reverse it, denoising pure noise back into a sample."},{"term":"Gaussian process","desc":"A prior over functions defined by a kernel; it gives predictions with error bars that widen away from the data."},{"term":"MCMC","desc":"Markov Chain Monte Carlo (e.g. Metropolis–Hastings): sample from a hard, unnormalized distribution by proposing moves and accepting them by a ratio."}]};
